commentBody:
@Barry Ancona

Yes.

After I realized "No slashes required".

@Barry Ancona

I replied to you but apparently the ADDLED EMUs chopped it up with their GINSUs to add to their KSTEW.

I said I was shocked that anything in these comments shocks you these days.

@Mike

“I’m not doing a rebus today.”
“Artoo.”

@Renegator

I was talking about begrudgingly, but in any case, after some thought on the matter, I offer my begrudging admission that I was wrong.

The clue was constructed in a way that I found difficult to parse at first.

@Sam Lyons

To be a traveling vet helping animals over the rainbow bridge is absolutely a calling, and I don't know how they do it without falling apart. They are not just doctors but grief counselors. 

My best wishes for Señor Gato's continued happy existence!

@Avi
WOOOOOOOOOW!

I didn't notice at all, but now that I do, that's amazing! Bravo, Brandon Koppy! That takes this puzzle to a whole 'nother level.

@MBM

As a new player, you criticize the NYT editors and constructors for creating a puzzle that you personally don't understand. They should gear *all* the puzzles towards newbies, not just the Mondays and Tuesdays.

Do I have that right?

@HeathieJ

Yeah, "Lars and the Real Girl" was surprisingly poignant.  I have to admit Ryan Gosling has taken on some very interesting and challenging roles.  

Even if I do despise him because he's devastatingly handsome.

@Matthew

There are valid reasons to be irritated by rebus puzzles.

However, none of them is "words are being misspelled".

@Beth

Oh my gosh that song takes up rent free space in my brain way too often!! 

Trying to avoid an earworm today!

@Whoa Nellie

Whoa Nellie!

it's fun, fun, fun, til yer daddy takes the t-bird away

@John

If it’s a variant (and therefore in the dictionaries), how can it be a misspelling?

When I got to that clue, the first thing I did was look at what 127A was. Seeing that I’d need NEO, I knew which one it was going to be.

@John
Merriam-Webster says ABETTER is a variant spelling. Just because something is uncommon doesn't mean it's wrong. I would also assume this was an easy mistake to spot, as "noolithic" is not a thing.

<a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/abet" target="_blank">https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/abet</a>

@Jane Wheelaghan It's not so much celebrated as it is a nod for the nerds and Sci-Fi fanatics, as is Pi Day.

Lettuce wraps are almost never a bunless grill item. Although I'm a closet vegetarian, I'd have opted for wursts or ribs, myself.

Ginsu knives was an over-the-top TV advert with the nutty inventor presenting a much-too-excited delivery of this product (more of a gimmic). It was easy to remember the brand because of his zaniness.

@Steve L et Alia,

Here you go:

<a href="https://youtu.be/_I0KmyqNXCE?si=5SX6zLiyCQbfJB4L" target="_blank">https://youtu.be/_I0KmyqNXCE?si=5SX6zLiyCQbfJB4L</a>

@Oikofuge

To me, LETTUCE WRAPS are a Vietnamese thing. (Probably other cuisines as well.)

It was gettable enough from the crosses...

@Sarah

There are 8 "misspelled" words, but not really.  Each one contains a rebus and they are part of the theme. 

(AU)GUSTA crosses IRS (AU)DITS.

@Nancy J.

Edit:

I should have said there are 16 "misspelled words"

@Jane Wheelaghan

Similar! I wanted the theme of this puzzle to be "Live long and prosper," but quickly realized the letters didn't fit. Took a little longer to notice the date.

Gotta say though, watching one of the later Star Wars episodes on a 5-story high curved IMAX screen with subwoofers under each seat was a whole different experience. The story line took a back seat to the experience of being _in_ that world.

@Jerry
I'm referring to a little earlier - 1963 ish.
Maybe the Beatles had more of an impact at that time in the UK? The country really started to change - not just music and fashion, but our way of life.

@Rich in Atlanta

Very fine post!

It's amazing how a puzzle can elicit so much creativity between constructors and solvers (like you).

@Barry Ancona

Thanks, but all I see are dates, no times.

I get only two links in the email notifications I receive.

@Byron

It started out as kind of a sports car, then got bigger and bigger until it was sedan sized, then got redone to a smaller size and regained the kind-of-a-sports-car status.

Just after that happened I was driving on I-85 in Atlanta, approaching the Connector from the north, and was passed by one of the newly redesigned T-birds. I thought about what a good job some designer had done on that car...it nicely recalled the original design, but updated it just enough...and was wondering who was responsible for it as I punched the radio on to the NPR station and Fresh Air, with some guy in mid-sentence. After maybe a minute I realized that Terry Gross was interviewing the very man responsible for the T-bird's redesign, and the one that had just passed me was still in sight.

@David Reiffel

Too bad we weren't neighbors, my dad had a bright orange 1970 stingray Corvette. My brother still has it.

My model right now isn't very exciting in comparison (Chevy Trax) but it is bright orange and I love it!

@Bruce

I remember being impressed with the T bird revival. Reminded me of a Fiat Spyder which is a nice looking car. I guess they are fairly sporty. 

Love listening to NPR whenever I’m in the US. A ritual with me is find the local NPR station (if I drove or am renting) and leave it there for the duration. I was in Palm Springs area years ago and they were doing the life and music of Johnny Cash the whole three days I was there. Really interesting.

@David Reiffel

Ha. 

My dad never had a T bird but he did have a 1972 red Superbug — in the early 80s! I learned how to drive in that car.

@Jane Wheelaghan 
This is the opening crawl of the first Star Wars movie. I would call it iconic. All the movies start with a crawl.


<a href="https://youtu.be/iXDnFYu91vY?si=Zv0SMlsW0kQ_ouj7" target="_blank">https://youtu.be/iXDnFYu91vY?si=Zv0SMlsW0kQ_ouj7</a>

@Emily

First letter is a rebus: AU
...then GUSTA

@Steve L

Yes but this is the exact same comment that showed up on Friday (when it was a Weintraub puzzle, of course).

More Comments poltergeists??

@Gk

It should. There's a rebus in there, as part of the theme. LET[TU]CEWRAP.
I've no idea what a lettuce wrap is.

@Mantelli

Rebuses seem gimmicky to me. 

Harrumph!

@Jacqueline

Imagine what it's like to be a Christmas baby! At some point you have to just sigh and move on... 

Happy birthday!! May the April showers have brought you lots of May flowers! 🌈💐🎉

@Barry Ancona

You know that's a little unfair, given there are over 250 comments and counting. 

@Laura M didn't say *no one* was commenting on that aspect of the puzzle. I think it's odd Caitlin didn't mention it in the column!

@Cristian L

It looks fine to me. 

You did realize that it’s a rebus puzzle, right?

@Barry Ancona

Thanks. 

I am not very good at solving meta puzzles. The STAR WARS in this puzzle is an example of how unobservant I sometimes am.

@Esmerelda

Loved the video and will save. Thanks so much. 

I'm familiar with the Tordon herbicide (picloram) that was mentioned.  Very nasty stuff.

@Barry Ancona

Same! 

Perhaps it's the emus' way of being clever... Too clever by half (as some on these boards like to say, haha!).

@G
Great puzzle! Genuinely curious if this is the same Gary Larson who makes the Far Side comics.

(Right in line with comments by Eddie and that guy from Mars earlier last year.)

@Xword Junkie
Did you notice that it's always the fourth letter of the across word that takes the +U rebus?

May the FOURTH be with U.

@Xword Junkie

Thanks for taking the time to do this. :-)

I actually saw your reply, because I could link straight from my email notification to my reply---which seems to open up the reply chain in the same way the "see all replies" button used to, before it vanished.

@Lucas

The first rebus puzzle appeared in 1955 (two years before I did). The fact that you’re unaware of this type of puzzle doesn’t mean it’s not a proper crossword. It just means it’s something you’re not familiar with. 

No one is pretending. Those who say they like it actually like it.

@Lucas

By the way, in case you haven't noticed, most of us thought that this was an extremely clever and satisfying STAR WARS themed puzzle, and not too difficult.

Please make yours even more clever and more difficult!

@Lucas

Some people like xword puzzles to be straightforward, and some appreciate the challenge of extra twists and turns.

The NYT xwords often have some extra twists and turns.

@MA

Did you refresh?

When my entries disappear, I try that and it works.

@Nick

I love how you included Margaret Thatcher becoming Prime Minister as a tragedy.  

I absolutely agree.

@Gail and Bill

I'm glad you still got it in a good for you time and smiled! I also put an O in there first, but then when I had NOoLITHIC, I NoO (!)I was wrong and that there must be an alternate spelling, since it had to be NEO.

As I think it was Barry who said earlier, apologies if I'm miss attributing, use the crosses, Luke!  😉
